{{italic title}}

''' ''A Passage to Infinity : Medieval Indian Mathematics from Kerala and Its Impact'' '''<ref name="Passage">{{cite book|last=Joseph|first=George Gheverghese|title=A Passage to Infinity : Medieval Indian Mathematics from Kerala and Its Impact|publisher=Sage Publications (Inda) Pvt. Ltd. |location=Delhi|date=2009|pages=236|isbn=978-81-321-0168-0}}</ref> is a book by George Gheverghese Joseph chronicling the social and mathematical origins of the [[Kerala school of astronomy and mathematics]]. The book discusses the highlights of the achievements of [[Kerala school of astronomy and mathematics|Kerala school]] and also analyses the hypotheses and conjectures on  the possible transmission of Kerala mathematics to [[Europe]].

==An outline of the contents==

# Introduction 
# The Social Origins of the [[Kerala school of astronomy and mathematics|Kerala School]] 
# The Mathematical Origins of the [[Kerala school of astronomy and mathematics|Kerala School]]
# The Highlights of [[Kerala]] [[Mathematics]] and [[Astronomy]]
# [[History of trigonometry#Indian mathematics|Indian Trigonometry]]: From Ancient Beginnings to [[Nilakantha Somayaji|Nilakantha]]
# [[Squaring the circle|Squaring the Circle]]: The Kerala Answer
# Reaching for the Stars: The [[Power Series]] for [[Sine]]s and [[Cosine]]s
# Changing Perspectives on [[Indian Mathematics]] 
# Exploring Transmissions: A Case Study of Kerala Mathematics
# A Final Assessment

