{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}} {{Use British English|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox university | name = University of Edinburgh School of Physics and Astronomy | image = [[File:James Clerk Maxwell Building - geograph.org.uk - 1762018.jpg|frameless|James Clerk Maxwell Building]] | head_label = | head = | academic_staff = | administrative_staff = | students = | undergrad = | postgrad = | doctoral = | campus = James Clerk Maxwell Building, [[King's Buildings]], [[Edinburgh]], Scotland | affiliation = [[EPCC]], [[Institute of Physics]] | website = {{url|www.ph.ed.ac.uk}} }}
The '''University of Edinburgh School of Physics and Astronomy''' is the [[physics]] department of the [[University of Edinburgh]]. The school was formed in 1993 by a merger of the Department of Physics - called the Department of Natural Philosophy until the late 1960s - and the Department of Astronomy, both at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. The school is part of the University's [[University of Edinburgh College of Science and Engineering|College of Science and Engineering]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About the School of Physics and Astronomy|url=http://www.ph.ed.ac.uk/about/school|publisher=[[University of Edinburgh]]|accessdate=1 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Physics Quality Profiles, Research Assessment Exercise 2008|url=http://www.rae.ac.uk/Results/qualityProfile.aspx?id=19&type=uoa|accessdate=1 August 2012}}</ref>
==Institutes== Institutions and research groups based within the school include: * '''Institute for Astronomy (IfA)''' - One of the UK's major centres of astronomical research, specialising in survey astronomy, [[cosmology]], active galaxies and the formation of stars and planets. * '''Institute for Condensed Matter and Complex Systems (ICMCS) * '''Institute for Particle and Nuclear Physics (IPNP) * '''EPCC''' - One of the leading supercomputing centres in Europe, home to the UK's national supercomputing service, [[HECToR]]. * '''[[Higgs Centre for Theoretical Physics]]''' - A new centre established in 2012 to "seek an even deeper understanding of how the universe works."<ref>{{cite web|title=University to support new physics research|url=http://www.ed.ac.uk/news/all-news/higgscentre-050712|publisher=University of Edinburgh|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref>
The school is housed in the James Clerk Maxwell Building on the University's [[King's Buildings]] campus.
==Notable people== {{see|List of University of Edinburgh people#Mathematics, physics and engineering}} Notable physicists associated with the University have included [[Joseph Black]], [[Max Born]], [[Peter Higgs]], [[James Clerk Maxwell]] and [[Peter Guthrie Tait]]. Five winners of the [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] are associated with the University ([[Edward Victor Appleton]], [[Charles Glover Barkla]], [[Max Born]], [[Igor Tamm]] and [[Peter Higgs]]).
